Use a dual-memory design: keep safety constraints in a stable, separately versioned policy layer while task learning updates only a narrower adaptive layer. Train with constrained optimization or loss penalties that make violating safety rules more costly than missing task performance gains. Rehearse safety-critical examples continuously, including adversarial and rare edge cases, so new fine-tuning is always interleaved with old safety behaviors. Add parameter isolation methods such as freezing, adapters, or orthogonal updates to reduce overwriting of safety-relevant representations. Run every model update through a regression suite with red-team evaluations, and block deployment if any safety metric degrades beyond a strict threshold. At inference time, enforce external safeguards like policy checkers, tool permissions, and refusal classifiers so safety does not depend solely on remembered weights. Maintain auditable data provenance and update logs so unsafe drift can be traced, rolled back, and corrected quickly.
